{"title_page": "Kiev City State Administration", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Kiev City Council}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name           = Kiev City State Administration\n| official_name           =  Kyiv City State Administration\n| native_name = \u041a\u0438\u0457\u0432\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0430 \u043c\u0456\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0430 \u0434\u0435\u0440\u0436\u0430\u0432\u043d\u0430 \u0430\u0434\u043c\u0456\u043d\u0456\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0456\u044f\n| native_name_lang        = uk\n| settlement_type         = [[City with special status]]\n| image_skyline  = \u041a\u0440\u0435\u0449\u0430\u0442\u0438\u043a, 36 (01) - \u041c\u044d\u0440\u0438\u044f.jpg\n| image_shield            = COA of Kyiv Kurovskyi.svg\n| shield_size             = 50px\n| shield_alt              = \n| shield_link             = \n| image_flag     = Flag of Kyiv Kurovskyi.svg\n| flag_size               = 100px\n| flag_alt                = \n| flag_link               =\n| leader_title            = Head\n| leader_name             = [[Vitali Klitschko]], [[Petro Poroshenko Bloc]]<br>since {{start date and age|2014|6|25|df=y}}<ref name=\"Poroshenko appoints Klitschko head of Kyiv city administration - decree\"/>\n| blank_name_sec1 = Administration center\n| blank_info_sec1 = 36 [[Khreshchatyk]] street, [[Kiev]], [[Ukraine]]\n| phone_code     =\n| postal_index   =\n| website        = https://kyivcity.gov.ua/\n}}\n\n'''Kiev City State Administration''', spelled '''''Kyiv'' City State Administration''' in its own letterhead<ref>{{Citation|title=File:Kyiv City State Administration Letter to WMF.jpg|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Kyiv_City_State_Administration_Letter_to_WMF.jpg|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2019-10-10}}</ref> ({{lang-uk|\u041a\u0438\u0457\u0432\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0430 \u043c\u0456\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0430 \u0434\u0435\u0440\u0436\u0430\u0432\u043d\u0430 \u0430\u0434\u043c\u0456\u043d\u0456\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0456\u044f|translit=Kyivska miska derzhavna administratsiia}}), is the national-level branch of the [[Government of Ukraine]] that administers [[Kiev]], the capital of [[Ukraine]]. The current Head of the Kiev City State Administration is [[Vitali Klitschko]]; Klitschko is also the current [[Mayor of Kiev]].<ref name=\"Poroshenko appoints Klitschko head of Kyiv city administration - decree\">[http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/210904.html Poroshenko appoints Klitschko head of Kyiv city administration - decree], [[Interfax-Ukraine]] (25 June 2014)<br>[http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/210980.html Poroshenko orders Klitschko to bring title of best European capital back to Kyiv], [[Interfax-Ukraine]] (25 June 2014)</ref><ref name=\"7238815KCSAChampion\"/>\n\n==Special status==\nKiev is a \"[[City with special status (Ukraine)|city with special status]]\" ({{lang-uk|\u043c\u0456\u0441\u0442\u043e \u0437\u0456 \u0441\u043f\u0435\u0446\u0456\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0438\u043c \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0443\u0441\u043e\u043c}}) within Ukraine compared to the other [[Administrative divisions of Ukraine|administrative subdivisions of the country]] \u2014 the most significant difference is that the city is subordinated directly to the national-level branches of the Government of Ukraine, skipping the [[oblast|regional level authorities]] of [[Kyiv Oblast]].<ref name=\"Chernihiv\" /> Its special administrative status is recognized in the [[Constitution of Ukraine|Ukrainian Constitution]] in [[:s:Constitution of Ukraine#Chapter IX: Territorial Structure of Ukraine|Chapter IX: Territorial Structure of Ukraine]] and the ''Law on the local state administration''<ref name=localstate /> and is governed in accordance with laws passed by Ukraine's parliament, the [[Verkhovna Rada]].<ref name=\"Kuibida\" /><ref name=lawkiev /><ref name=annot /><ref name=Const2001 />\n\nLocal government is carried out by [[Kyiv City Council]] and district councils, headed by their chairpersons who are elected from among the councilors.\n\nAlthough Kyiv is Ukraine's capital, the city also serves as the [[Administrative centre|administrative center]] for [[Kyiv Oblast]] ([[Oblasts of Ukraine|province]]). The oblast entirely surrounds the city, making it into an enclave. In addition, Kyiv also serves as the administrative center for the oblast's [[Kyiv-Sviatoshyn Raion]] ([[Raions of Ukraine|district]]).\n\nAccording to the Constitution the head of the Kiev City State Administration should resign after a [[Ukrainian presidential elections|new President is elected]].<ref name=\"7238815KCSAChampion\">{{in lang|uk}} [https://www.pravda.com.ua/articles/2020/01/30/7238815/ City Champion. How Klitschko kept Kyiv], [[Ukrayinska Pravda]] (30 January 2020)</ref> \n\n===2010 amendments===\n{{Ukraine subdivisions sidebar}}\n\nThe [[Ukrainian parliament]] amended the law on \"The capital of Ukraine \u2013 [[hero city]] of Kiev\" on September 7, 2010 making it possible for the [[Ukrainian President|President]] to appoint the (chairman) Head of Kiev City Administration at his discretion. Before these amendments, the elected mayor of the [[Kiev City Council]] was automatically appointed also as head of the Kiev City State Administration.<ref name=\"Grimskaya\" /><ref name=\"Marta Grimskaya\">[http://www.docstoc.com/docs/67848764/See-in-Content-Political-Risk Political Risks and Political Stability in Ukraine], [[UCIPR]] (October 2010)</ref> A Presidential decree relieved (then) [[Mayor of Kyiv]] [[Leonid Chernovetsky]] of the office of \"Head of the Kiev State Administration\", while still preserving the post of mayor.<ref name=\"Marta Grimskaya\"/> This led to Chernovetsky being deprived of any official decision-making role and most power in the capital was handed over to the Head of Kiev City Administration.<ref name=\"QofEngland\"/><ref name=\"kyivpost1\">[http://www.kyivpost.com/news/nation/detail/96079/ Popov: Activity of city council and city head limited], [[Kyiv Post]] (February 1, 2011)</ref><ref name=\"2012electionsKyiv\">[http://www.kyivpost.com/news/city/detail/90367/ Party of Regions leader: 'Pre-term mayoral elections in Kyiv are pointless'], [[Kyiv Post]] (November 18, 2011)</ref>\n\n[[Oleksandr Popov]] was then appointed as Head of Kyiv City Administration by President [[Viktor Yanukovych]] on 16 November 2010.<ref name=\"QofEngland\" /><ref name=\"kyivpost1\" /><ref name=\"2012electionsKyiv\"/> On 14 December 2013 President Yanukovych suspended Popov.<ref name=Yanusend141213>[http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/181863.html  Yanukovych suspends Kyiv City Administration Head Popov and Deputy NSDC Secretary Sivkovych from office, say decrees], [[Interfax-Ukraine]] (14 December 2013)<br>[http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/181855.html Deputy NSDC Head Sivkovych, Kyiv City Administration Head Popov and two top officials of Kyiv police suspected of abuse of power during events on Maidan on Nov 30, says prosecutor general], [[Interfax-Ukraine]] (14 December 2013)</ref> The same day the [[General Prosecutor of Ukraine]]'s Office handed \"a notification on suspicion of abuse of power when ordering the [[Euromaidan]] [[Timeline of the Euromaidan#30 November attack on protesters|police actions of 30 November 2013]]\" out to Popov<ref name=Yanusend141213/> and [[Anatoliy Holubchenko]] was appointed as [[Acting (law)|acting]] Head of Kiev City Administration.<ref name=141213nhca>{{in lang|uk}} [http://www.rbc.ua/ukr/news/politics/yanukovich-otstranil-popova-ot-dolzhnosti-glavy-kgga-14122013140800/ \u042f\u043d\u0443\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0432\u0456\u0434\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0438\u0432 \u041f\u043e\u043f\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u0437 \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0430\u0434\u0438 \u0433\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0438 \u041a\u041c\u0414\u0410 ''Yanukovych dismissed Popov as head of Kiev City State Administration''], [[RBC Ukraine]] (14 December 2013)<br>[http://www.unn.com.ua/en/news/1284261-v-opozitsiyi-zazhadali-yaknayshvidshogo-priznachennya-dati-viboriv-mera-kiyeva-i-stolichnoyi-miskradi The opposition demanded an early appointment of the date of elections of Kyiv mayor and Kyiv city council] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131214184739/http://www.unn.com.ua/en/news/1284261-v-opozitsiyi-zazhadali-yaknayshvidshogo-priznachennya-dati-viboriv-mera-kiyeva-i-stolichnoyi-miskradi |date=2013-12-14 }}, [[Ukrainian National News]] (14 December 2013)</ref> On 24 December 2013 Holubchenko stated that he regularly met with (his predecessor) Popov.<ref>[http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/183702.html Popov feels fine \u2013 Holubchenko], [[Interfax-Ukraine]] (24 December 2013)</ref> [[Volodymyr Makeyenko]] was appointed Head of Kiev City Administration on 25 January 2014 by President Yanukovych.<ref name=PhKCA/> The same day Popov was fired as Head of Kiev City Administration.<ref name=PhKCA>[http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/187386.html Yanukovych fires Kyiv City Administration head Popov, appoints MP Makeyenko], [[Interfax-Ukraine]] (25 January 2014)</ref> Acting President [[Oleksandr Turchynov]] dismissed Makeyenko from the post of the head of Kiev City State Administration on 7 March 2014 and gave the post to [[Volodymyr Bondarenko (politician)|Volodymyr Bondarenko]]<ref name=\"kyivpost.com\">http://www.kyivpost.com/content/kyiv/volodymyr-bondarenko-of-batkivschyna-faction-heads-kyiv-administration-338763.html</ref> (Then) newly elected President [[Petro Poroshenko]] appointed on 25 June 2014 [[Vitali Klitschko]]; who is the current [[Mayor of Kiev]] since 5 June 2014.<ref name=\"Poroshenko appoints Klitschko head of Kyiv city administration - decree\"/><ref name=KKMs5614>[http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/208052.html Vitali Klitschko sworn in as Kyiv mayor], [[Interfax-Ukraine]] (5 June 2014)</ref>\n\n==List of heads==\n\n* 1990\u20131991 [[Hryhoriy Malyshevsky]] (from [[Boryspil Raion]]) (as head of city executive committee, simultaneously city's mayor)\n** 1991\u20131992 [[Oleksandr Mosiyuk]] (from [[Lutsk]]) (as acting head of city executive committee, simultaneously acting city's mayor)\n* March 1992 [[Ivan Dankevych]] (from [[Bobrovytsia Raion]]) (as head of city executive committee)\n* March 1992\u2013April 1993 [[Ivan Saliy]] (from [[Ichnia Raion]]) (as Presidential representative and city's governor)\n** April 1993 [[Ivan Dankevych]] (from [[Bobrovytsia Raion]]) (as acting)\n* April 1993\u2013July 1994 [[Leonid Kosakivsky]] (from [[Mohyliv-Podilskyi Raion]]) (as Presidential representative)\n* July 1995\u2013July 1996 [[Leonid Kosakivsky]] (from [[Mohyliv-Podilskyi Raion]]) (as Head of Kyiv City Administration) (mayor in 1994-1998)\n* August 1996\u2013April 2006 [[Oleksandr Omelchenko]] (from [[Lypovets Raion]]) (as Head of Kyiv City Administration) (mayor in 1999-2006)\n* April 2006\u2013November 2010 [[Leonid Chernovetskyi]] (from [[Kharkiv]]) (as Head of Kyiv City Administration) (mayor in 2006-2012)\n* November 2010\u2013December 2013 [[Oleksandr Popov]] (from [[Kryvyi Rih]]) (as Head of Kyiv City Administration)\n** December 2013\u2013January 2014 [[Anatoliy Holubchenko]] (from [[Mariupol]]) (acting)\n* January 25, 2014\u2013March 7, 2014 [[Volodymyr Makeyenko]] (from [[Klintsy]], [[Russia]]) (as Head of Kyiv City Administration)\n* March 7, 2014\u2013June 25, 2014 [[Volodymyr Bondarenko (politician)|Volodymyr Bondarenko]]<ref name=\"kyivpost.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Bondarenko is appointed Head of the Kyiv City State Administration|url=http://www.pravda.com.ua/news/2014/03/7/7018103/|work=[[Ukrayinska Pravda]]|accessdate=7 March 2014|language=Ukrainian}}</ref>\n* June 25, 2014\u2013present [[Vitali Klitschko]]<ref name=\"Poroshenko appoints Klitschko head of Kyiv city administration - decree\"/><ref>[http://www.kyivpost.com/content/ukraine/poroshenko-appoints-klitschko-as-head-of-kyiv-city-administration-353335.html Poroshenko appoints Klitschko as head of Kyiv city administration], [[Kyiv Post]] (June 25, 2014)</ref> (mayor in 2014\u2013present)\n\n==See also==\n* [[Subdivisions of Kiev]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2|refs=\n<ref name=\"Chernihiv\">{{cite web|title=Cities with special status|url=http://www.center.uct.ua/distants/courses/pu01/htm/p03_help/h51.html|work=Chernihiv Center for Professional Development|language=Ukrainian|accessdate=17 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120722215928/http://www.center.uct.ua/distants/courses/pu01/htm/p03_help/h51.html|archivedate=22 July 2012}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Kuibida\">{{cite web|last=Kuibida |first=Vasyl |title=The concept of reform of the administrative-territorial structure of Ukraine. Project |url=http://bizvolnet.org.ua/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=206&Itemid=82 |work=Kyiv Regional Center for International Relations and Business |accessdate=7 February 2012 |language=Ukrainian |date=18 November 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140415132531/http://bizvolnet.org.ua/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=206&Itemid=82 |archivedate=15 April 2014 }}</ref>\n<ref name=QofEngland>[http://www.kyivpost.com/news/nation/detail/93068/ #14 Richest: Leonid Chernovetsky, 59], [[Kyiv Post]] (December 17, 2010)</ref>\n<ref name=\"kyivpost1\">[http://www.kyivpost.com/news/nation/detail/96079/ Popov: Activity of city council and city head limited], [[Kyiv Post]] (February 1, 2011)</ref>\n<ref name=\"2012electionsKyiv\">[http://www.kyivpost.com/news/city/detail/90367/ Party of Regions leader: 'Pre-term mayoral elections in Kyiv are pointless'], [[Kyiv Post]] (November 18, 2011)</ref>\n<ref name=\"Grimskaya\">[http://www.docstoc.com/docs/67848764/See-in-Content-Political-Risk Political Risks and Political Stability in Ukraine], UCIPR (October 2010)</ref>\n<ref name=lawkiev>[http://zakon.rada.gov.ua/cgi-bin/laws/main.cgi?nreg=401%2D14 The Law of Ukraine \"On the Capital of Ukraine \u2014 Hero City Kiev\"] dated January 15, 1999 {{in lang|uk}}</ref>\n<ref name=annot>[http://zakon.rada.gov.ua/cgi-bin/laws/anot.cgi?nreg=401%2D14  Annotation to the Law] {{in lang|en}}</ref>\n<ref name=Const2001>[http://zakon.rada.gov.ua/cgi-bin/laws/main.cgi?nreg=v011p710%2D01 Interpretation of certain terms in the Law] by the [[Constitutional Court of Ukraine]] {{in lang|uk}}</ref>\n<ref name=localstate>[http://zakon.rada.gov.ua/cgi-bin/laws/main.cgi?nreg=586-14 The Law of Ukraine on the Local State Administration] last amended December 21, 2006 {{in lang|uk}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite web|title=Official internet-portal|url=https://kyivcity.gov.ua/|work=Kiev City State Administration|accessdate=7 March 2014|language=Ukrainian}}\n\nTelegram - https://t.me/KyivCityOfficial\n\n{{Administrative divisions of Ukraine}}\n{{Chairmen of regional state administrations of Ukraine}}\n\n[[Category:Government of Kiev| ]]\n[[Category:Chiefs of Local State Administration (Ukraine)|Kiev]]\n[[Category:Governors of Kiev|*]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Kiev City Council}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name           = Kiev City State Administration\n| official_name           =  Kyiv City State Administration\n| native_name = \u041a\u0438\u0457\u0432\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0430 \u043c\u0456\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0430 \u0434\u0435\u0440\u0436\u0430\u0432\u043d\u0430 \u0430\u0434\u043c\u0456\u043d\u0456\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0456\u044f\n| native_name_lang        = uk\n| settlement_type         = [[City with special status]]\n| image_skyline  = \u041a\u0440\u0435\u0449\u0430\u0442\u0438\u043a, 36 (01) - \u041c\u044d\u0440\u0438\u044f.jpg\n| image_shield            = COA of Kyiv Kurovskyi.svg\n| shield_size             = 50px\n| shield_alt              = \n| shield_link             = \n| image_flag     = Flag of Kyiv Kurovskyi.svg\n| flag_size               = 100px\n| flag_alt                = \n| flag_link               =\n| leader_title            = Head\n| leader_name             = [[Vitali Klitschko]], [[Petro Poroshenko Bloc]]<br>since {{start date and age|2014|6|25|df=y}}<ref name=\"Poroshenko appoints Klitschko head of Kyiv city administration - decree\"/>\n| blank_name_sec1 = Administration center\n| blank_info_sec1 = 36 [[Khreshchatyk]] street, [[Kiev]], [[Ukraine]]\n| phone_code     =\n| postal_index   =\n| website        = https://kyivcity.gov.ua/\n}}\n\n'''Kiev City State Administration''', spelled '''''Kyiv'' City State Administration''' in its own letterhead<ref>{{Citation|title=File:Kyiv City State Administration Letter to WMF.jpg|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Kyiv_City_State_Administration_Letter_to_WMF.jpg|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2019-10-10}}</ref> ({{lang-uk|\u041a\u0438\u0457\u0432\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0430 \u043c\u0456\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0430 \u0434\u0435\u0440\u0436\u0430\u0432\u043d\u0430 \u0430\u0434\u043c\u0456\u043d\u0456\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0456\u044f|translit=Kyivska miska derzhavna administratsiia}}), is the national-level branch of the [[Government of Ukraine]] that administers [[Kiev]], the capital of [[Ukraine]]. The current Head of the Kiev City State Administration is [[Vitali Klitschko]]; Klitschko is also the current [[Mayor of Kiev]].<ref name=\"Poroshenko appoints Klitschko head of Kyiv city administration - decree\">[http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/210904.html Poroshenko appoints Klitschko head of Kyiv city administration - decree], [[Interfax-Ukraine]] (25 June 2014)<br>[http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/210980.html Poroshenko orders Klitschko to bring title of best European capital back to Kyiv], [[Interfax-Ukraine]] (25 June 2014)</ref><ref name=\"7238815KCSAChampion\"/>\n\n==Special status==\nKiev is a \"[[City with special status (Ukraine)|city with special status]]\" ({{lang-uk|\u043c\u0456\u0441\u0442\u043e \u0437\u0456 \u0441\u043f\u0435\u0446\u0456\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0438\u043c \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0443\u0441\u043e\u043c}}) within Ukraine compared to the other [[Administrative divisions of Ukraine|administrative subdivisions of the country]] \u2014 the most significant difference is that the city is subordinated directly to the national-level branches of the Government of Ukraine, skipping the [[oblast|regional level authorities]] of [[Kyiv Oblast]].<ref name=\"Chernihiv\" /> Its special administrative status is recognized in the [[Constitution of Ukraine|Ukrainian Constitution]] in [[:s:Constitution of Ukraine#Chapter IX: Territorial Structure of Ukraine|Chapter IX: Territorial Structure of Ukraine]] and the ''Law on the local state administration''<ref name=localstate /> and is governed in accordance with laws passed by Ukraine's parliament, the [[Verkhovna Rada]].<ref name=\"Kuibida\" /><ref name=lawkiev /><ref name=annot /><ref name=Const2001 />\n\nLocal government is carried out by [[Kyiv City Council]] and district councils, headed by their chairpersons who are elected from among the councilors.\n\nAlthough Kyiv is Ukraine's capital, the city also serves as the [[Administrative centre|administrative center]] for [[Kyiv Oblast]] ([[Oblasts of Ukraine|province]]). The oblast entirely surrounds the city, making it into an enclave. In addition, Kyiv also serves as the administrative center for the oblast's [[Kyiv-Sviatoshyn Raion]] ([[Raions of Ukraine|district]]).\n\nAccording to the Constitution the head of the Kiev City State Administration should resign after a [[Ukrainian presidential elections|new President is elected]].<ref name=\"7238815KCSAChampion\">{{in lang|uk}} [https://www.pravda.com.ua/articles/2020/01/30/7238815/ City Champion. How Klitschko kept Kyiv], [[Ukrayinska Pravda]] (30 January 2020)</ref> \n\n===2010 amendments===\n{{Ukraine subdivisions sidebar}}\n\nThe [[Ukrainian parliament]] amended the law on \"The capital of Ukraine \u2013 [[hero city]] of Kiev\" on September 7, 2010 making it possible for the [[Ukrainian President|President]] to appoint the (chairman) Head of Kiev City Administration at his discretion. Before these amendments, the elected mayor of the [[Kiev City Council]] was automatically appointed also as head of the Kiev City State Administration.<ref name=\"Grimskaya\" /><ref name=\"Marta Grimskaya\">[http://www.docstoc.com/docs/67848764/See-in-Content-Political-Risk Political Risks and Political Stability in Ukraine], [[UCIPR]] (October 2010)</ref> A Presidential decree relieved (then) [[Mayor of Kyiv]] [[Leonid Chernovetsky]] of the office of \"Head of the Kiev State Administration\", while still preserving the post of mayor.<ref name=\"Marta Grimskaya\"/> This led to Chernovetsky being deprived of any official decision-making role and most power in the capital was handed over to the Head of Kiev City Administration.<ref name=\"QofEngland\"/><ref name=\"kyivpost1\">[http://www.kyivpost.com/news/nation/detail/96079/ Popov: Activity of city council and city head limited], [[Kyiv Post]] (February 1, 2011)</ref><ref name=\"2012electionsKyiv\">[http://www.kyivpost.com/news/city/detail/90367/ Party of Regions leader: 'Pre-term mayoral elections in Kyiv are pointless'], [[Kyiv Post]] (November 18, 2011)</ref>\n\n[[Oleksandr Popov]] was then appointed as Head of Kyiv City Administration by President [[Viktor Yanukovych]] on 16 November 2010.<ref name=\"QofEngland\" /><ref name=\"kyivpost1\" /><ref name=\"2012electionsKyiv\"/> On 14 December 2013 President Yanukovych suspended Popov.<ref name=Yanusend141213>[http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/181863.html  Yanukovych suspends Kyiv City Administration Head Popov and Deputy NSDC Secretary Sivkovych from office, say decrees], [[Interfax-Ukraine]] (14 December 2013)<br>[http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/181855.html Deputy NSDC Head Sivkovych, Kyiv City Administration Head Popov and two top officials of Kyiv police suspected of abuse of power during events on Maidan on Nov 30, says prosecutor general], [[Interfax-Ukraine]] (14 December 2013)</ref> The same day the [[General Prosecutor of Ukraine]]'s Office handed \"a notification on suspicion of abuse of power when ordering the [[Euromaidan]] [[Timeline of the Euromaidan#30 November attack on protesters|police actions of 30 November 2013]]\" out to Popov<ref name=Yanusend141213/> and [[Anatoliy Holubchenko]] was appointed as [[Acting (law)|acting]] Head of Kiev City Administration.<ref name=141213nhca>{{in lang|uk}} [http://www.rbc.ua/ukr/news/politics/yanukovich-otstranil-popova-ot-dolzhnosti-glavy-kgga-14122013140800/ \u042f\u043d\u0443\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0432\u0456\u0434\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0438\u0432 \u041f\u043e\u043f\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u0437 \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0430\u0434\u0438 \u0433\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0438 \u041a\u041c\u0414\u0410 ''Yanukovych dismissed Popov as head of Kiev City State Administration''], [[RBC Ukraine]] (14 December 2013)<br>[http://www.unn.com.ua/en/news/1284261-v-opozitsiyi-zazhadali-yaknayshvidshogo-priznachennya-dati-viboriv-mera-kiyeva-i-stolichnoyi-miskradi The opposition demanded an early appointment of the date of elections of Kyiv mayor and Kyiv city council] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131214184739/http://www.unn.com.ua/en/news/1284261-v-opozitsiyi-zazhadali-yaknayshvidshogo-priznachennya-dati-viboriv-mera-kiyeva-i-stolichnoyi-miskradi |date=2013-12-14 }}, [[Ukrainian National News]] (14 December 2013)</ref> On 24 December 2013 Holubchenko stated that he regularly met with (his predecessor) Popov.<ref>[http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/183702.html Popov feels fine \u2013 Holubchenko], [[Interfax-Ukraine]] (24 December 2013)</ref> [[Volodymyr Makeyenko]] was appointed Head of Kiev City Administration on 25 January 2014 by President Yanukovych.<ref name=PhKCA/> The same day Popov was fired as Head of Kiev City Administration.<ref name=PhKCA>[http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/187386.html Yanukovych fires Kyiv City Administration head Popov, appoints MP Makeyenko], [[Interfax-Ukraine]] (25 January 2014)</ref> Acting President [[Oleksandr Turchynov]] dismissed Makeyenko from the post of the head of Kiev City State Administration on 7 March 2014 and gave the post to [[Volodymyr Bondarenko (politician)|Volodymyr Bondarenko]]<ref name=\"kyivpost.com\">http://www.kyivpost.com/content/kyiv/volodymyr-bondarenko-of-batkivschyna-faction-heads-kyiv-administration-338763.html</ref> (Then) newly elected President [[Petro Poroshenko]] appointed on 25 June 2014 [[Vitali Klitschko]]; who is the current [[Mayor of Kiev]] since 5 June 2014.<ref name=\"Poroshenko appoints Klitschko head of Kyiv city administration - decree\"/><ref name=KKMs5614>[http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/208052.html Vitali Klitschko sworn in as Kyiv mayor], [[Interfax-Ukraine]] (5 June 2014)</ref>\n\n==List of heads==\n\n* 1990\u20131991 [[Hryhoriy Malyshevsky]] (from [[Boryspil Raion]]) (as head of city executive committee, simultaneously city's mayor)\n** 1991\u20131992 [[Oleksandr Mosiyuk]] (from [[Lutsk]]) (as acting head of city executive committee, simultaneously acting city's mayor)\n* March 1992 [[Ivan Dankevych]] (from [[Bobrovytsia Raion]]) (as head of city executive committee)\n* March 1992\u2013April 1993 [[Ivan Saliy]] (from [[Ichnia Raion]]) (as Presidential representative and city's governor)\n** April 1993 [[Ivan Dankevych]] (from [[Bobrovytsia Raion]]) (as acting)\n* April 1993\u2013July 1994 [[Leonid Kosakivsky]] (from [[Mohyliv-Podilskyi Raion]]) (as Presidential representative)\n* July 1995\u2013July 1996 [[Leonid Kosakivsky]] (from [[Mohyliv-Podilskyi Raion]]) (as Head of Kyiv City Administration) (mayor in 1994-1998)\n* August 1996\u2013April 2006 [[Oleksandr Omelchenko]] (from [[Lypovets Raion]]) (as Head of Kyiv City Administration) (mayor in 1999-2006)\n* April 2006\u2013November 2010 [[Leonid Chernovetskyi]] (from [[Kharkiv]]) (as Head of Kyiv City Administration) (mayor in 2006-2012)\n* November 2010\u2013December 2013 [[Oleksandr Popov]] (from [[Kryvyi Rih]]) (as Head of Kyiv City Administration)\n** December 2013\u2013January 2014 [[Anatoliy Holubchenko]] (from [[Mariupol]]) (acting)\n* January 25, 2014\u2013March 7, 2014 [[Volodymyr Makeyenko]] (from [[Klintsy]], [[Russia]]) (as Head of Kyiv City Administration)\n* March 7, 2014\u2013June 25, 2014 [[Volodymyr Bondarenko (politician)|Volodymyr Bondarenko]]<ref name=\"kyivpost.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Bondarenko is appointed Head of the Kyiv City State Administration|url=http://www.pravda.com.ua/news/2014/03/7/7018103/|work=[[Ukrayinska Pravda]]|accessdate=7 March 2014|language=Ukrainian}}</ref>\n* June 25, 2014\u2013present [[Vitali Klitschko]]<ref name=\"Poroshenko appoints Klitschko head of Kyiv city administration - decree\"/><ref>[http://www.kyivpost.com/content/ukraine/poroshenko-appoints-klitschko-as-head-of-kyiv-city-administration-353335.html Poroshenko appoints Klitschko as head of Kyiv city administration], [[Kyiv Post]] (June 25, 2014)</ref> (mayor in 2014\u2013present)\n\n==See also==\n* [[Subdivisions of Kiev]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2|refs=\n<ref name=\"Chernihiv\">{{cite web|title=Cities with special status|url=http://www.center.uct.ua/distants/courses/pu01/htm/p03_help/h51.html|work=Chernihiv Center for Professional Development|language=Ukrainian|accessdate=17 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120722215928/http://www.center.uct.ua/distants/courses/pu01/htm/p03_help/h51.html|archivedate=22 July 2012}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Kuibida\">{{cite web|last=Kuibida |first=Vasyl |title=The concept of reform of the administrative-territorial structure of Ukraine. Project |url=http://bizvolnet.org.ua/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=206&Itemid=82 |work=Kyiv Regional Center for International Relations and Business |accessdate=7 February 2012 |language=Ukrainian |date=18 November 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140415132531/http://bizvolnet.org.ua/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=206&Itemid=82 |archivedate=15 April 2014 }}</ref>\n<ref name=QofEngland>[http://www.kyivpost.com/news/nation/detail/93068/ #14 Richest: Leonid Chernovetsky, 59], [[Kyiv Post]] (December 17, 2010)</ref>\n<ref name=\"kyivpost1\">[http://www.kyivpost.com/news/nation/detail/96079/ Popov: Activity of city council and city head limited], [[Kyiv Post]] (February 1, 2011)</ref>\n<ref name=\"2012electionsKyiv\">[http://www.kyivpost.com/news/city/detail/90367/ Party of Regions leader: 'Pre-term mayoral elections in Kyiv are pointless'], [[Kyiv Post]] (November 18, 2011)</ref>\n<ref name=\"Grimskaya\">[http://www.docstoc.com/docs/67848764/See-in-Content-Political-Risk Political Risks and Political Stability in Ukraine], UCIPR (October 2010)</ref>\n<ref name=lawkiev>[http://zakon.rada.gov.ua/cgi-bin/laws/main.cgi?nreg=401%2D14 The Law of Ukraine \"On the Capital of Ukraine \u2014 Hero City Kiev\"] dated January 15, 1999 {{in lang|uk}}</ref>\n<ref name=annot>[http://zakon.rada.gov.ua/cgi-bin/laws/anot.cgi?nreg=401%2D14  Annotation to the Law] {{in lang|en}}</ref>\n<ref name=Const2001>[http://zakon.rada.gov.ua/cgi-bin/laws/main.cgi?nreg=v011p710%2D01 Interpretation of certain terms in the Law] by the [[Constitutional Court of Ukraine]] {{in lang|uk}}</ref>\n<ref name=localstate>[http://zakon.rada.gov.ua/cgi-bin/laws/main.cgi?nreg=586-14 The Law of Ukraine on the Local State Administration] last amended December 21, 2006 {{in lang|uk}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite web|title=Official internet-portal|url=https://kyivcity.gov.ua/|work=Kiev City State Administration|accessdate=7 March 2014|language=Ukrainian}}\n\n{{Administrative divisions of Ukraine}}\n{{Chairmen of regional state administrations of Ukraine}}\n\n[[Category:Government of Kiev| ]]\n[[Category:Chiefs of Local State Administration (Ukraine)|Kiev]]\n[[Category:Governors of Kiev|*]]\n", "name_user": "185.185.253.31", "label": "vandal", "comment": "(add telegram)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kiev_City_State_Administration"}
{"title_page": "Paul Snider", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Paul Snider\n| image         = \n| imagesize     = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = Paul Leslie Snider\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1951|4|15}}\n| birth_place   = [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]], Canada\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1980|8|14|1951|4|15}}\n| death_place   = [[West Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n| death_cause   = Suicide by gunshot\n| resting_place = Schara Tzedeck Cemetery, [[New Westminster]], British Columbia\n| nationality   = Canadian\n| occupation    = Entrepreneur<br />Manager\n| spouse        = {{marriage|[[Dorothy Stratten]]|1979}}\n}}\n'''Paul Leslie Snider''' (April 15, 1951 \u2013 August 14, 1980) was a Canadian who is best known for the rape and murder of  his estranged wife, the ''[[Playboy]]'' model [[Dorothy Stratten]]. Following her murder, he killed himself.<ref name=\"carpenter\">{{cite news\n  | title = Death of a Playmate\n  | last = Carpenter\n  | first = Theresa\n  | work = The Village Voice\n  | date = November 5, 1980\n  | url = http://www.teresacarpenter.com/voice_playmate.pdf\n  | accessdate = July 15, 2014}}</ref><ref>Michael H. Stone & Gary Brucato, ''The New Evil: Understanding the Emergence of Modern Violent Crime'' (Amherst, New York: Prometheus Books, 2019), pp. 53-57.</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\nSnider was born in [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]], to Jewish parents. By the mid-1970s, he was a night-club promoter and erstwhile [[pimp]].<ref name=\"carpenter\"/> In 1977, Snider met Dorothy Stratten at a Vancouver-area [[Dairy Queen]], where she was working part-time while still attending high school, and romanced her. In 1979, he sent professionally taken nude photographs of Stratten to ''[[Playboy]]'' magazine, and she was chosen as a [[Playboy Playmate|Playmate]] for the month of August that year. Snider and Stratten moved to [[Los Angeles]] and were married on June 1 in [[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas]].<ref name=\"Vargas\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/retropolis/wp/2017/09/29/hugh-hefner-the-murder-of-dorothy-stratten-and-the-dark-side-of-playboy/?pagewanted=all|title=Hugh Hefner, the murder of Dorothy Stratten and the dark side of Playboy|last=Vargas|first=Theresa|work=Washington Post|date=September 29, 2017|accessdate=18 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nWhile Stratten worked as a [[Playboy Bunny|bunny]] at the [[Century City]] [[Playboy Club]] and was cast in a few television and film roles, Snider had numerous get-rich-quick schemes, including building and selling exercise benches. Stratten helped support Snider financially throughout their short-lived marriage (as he was a Canadian with no working visa, and was not allowed an income within the U.S.).<ref name=\"carpenter\"/> In 1979, Snider formed a partnership with [[Somen Banerjee]] and the attorney Bruce Nahin to form what became the male [[strip club]] format of [[Chippendales]].\n\nIn 1980, Stratten was named ''Playboy''{{'}}s [[List of Playboy Playmates of the Year|Playmate of the Year]] and was cast in a motion picture, ''[[They All Laughed]]'' (1981) directed by [[Peter Bogdanovich]], with whom she began an affair. Stratten and Snider separated and he hired a [[private investigator]] to follow her.\n\n=== Death ===\nOn August 14, 1980, Stratten was shot and killed in the [[West Los Angeles]] house they had shared. Snider's body was found next to hers. Police believed he raped and murdered her, sexually abused the corpse, then killed himself with the same shotgun.<ref name=\"carpenter\"/><ref name=\"Canby\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/11/10/movies/screen-star-80-a-sex-symbol-s-life-and-death.html?pagewanted=all|title=Screen: 'Star 80,' a Sex-Symbol's Life and Death|last=Canby|first=Vincent|work=The New York Times|date=November 10, 1983|accessdate=2 May 2009}}</ref>\n\nSnider's remains are buried at Schara Tzedeck Cemetery in [[New Westminster]], [[British Columbia]], Canada.\n\n== In popular culture ==\nSnider has been portrayed in two films. The first was a made-for-television movie about the murder called ''[[Death of a Centerfold: The Dorothy Stratten Story]]'' (1981), which starred [[Jamie Lee Curtis]] as Stratten and [[Bruce Weitz]] as Snider. [[Bob Fosse]]'s feature film ''[[Star 80]]'' (1983) dramatized Stratten's life and death. [[Mariel Hemingway]] played Stratten and [[Eric Roberts]] portrayed Snider in a highly acclaimed performance.<ref name=\"Canby\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Find a Grave|4176}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Snider, Paul}}\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:1980 deaths]]\n[[Category:Murder\u2013suicides in California]]\n[[Category:People from Vancouver]]\n[[Category:Suicides by firearm in California]]\n[[Category:Canadian Jews]]\n[[Category:Burials in British Columbia]]\n[[Category:Canadian expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:Canadian murderers]]\n[[Category:Canadian rapists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian criminals]]\n[[Category:Canadian male criminals]]\n[[Category:Necrophiles]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Paul Snider\n| image         = \n| imagesize     = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = Paul Leslie Snider\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1951|4|15}}\n| birth_place   = [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]], Canada\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1980|8|14|1951|4|15}}\n| death_place   = [[West Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n| death_cause   = Suicide by gunshot\n| resting_place = Schara Tzedeck Cemetery, [[New Westminster]], British Columbia\n| nationality   = Canadian\n| occupation    = Entrepreneur<br />Manager\n| spouse        = {{marriage|[[Dorothy Stratten]]|1979}}\n}}\n'''Paul Leslie Snider''' (April 15, 1951 \u2013 August 14, 1980) was a Canadian who is best known for the rape and murder of  his estranged wife, the ''[[Playboy]]'' model [[Dorothy Stratten]]. Following her murder, he killed himself.<ref name=\"carpenter\">{{cite news\n  | title = Death of a Playmate\n  | last = Carpenter\n  | first = Theresa\n  | work = The Village Voice\n  | date = November 5, 1980\n  | url = http://www.teresacarpenter.com/voice_playmate.pdf\n  | accessdate = July 15, 2014}}</ref><ref>Michael H. Stone & Gary Brucato, ''The New Evil: Understanding the Emergence of Modern Violent Crime'' (Amherst, New York: Prometheus Books, 2019), pp. 53-57.</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\nSnider was born in [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]], to Jewish parents. By the mid-1970s, he was a night-club promoter and erstwhile [[pimp]].<ref name=\"carpenter\"/> In 1977, Snider met Dorothy Stratten at a Vancouver-area [[Dairy Queen]], where she was working part-time while still attending high school, and romanced her. In 1979, he sent professionally taken nude photographs of Stratten to ''[[Playboy]]'' magazine, and she was chosen as a [[Playboy Playmate|Playmate]] for the month of August that year. Snider and Stratten moved to [[Los Angeles]] and were married on June 1 in [[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas]].<ref name=\"Vargas\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/retropolis/wp/2017/09/29/hugh-hefner-the-murder-of-dorothy-stratten-and-the-dark-side-of-playboy/?pagewanted=all|title=Hugh Hefner, the murder of Dorothy Stratten and the dark side of Playboy|last=Vargas|first=Theresa|work=Washington Post|date=September 29, 2017|accessdate=18 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nWhile Stratten worked as a [[Playboy Bunny|bunny]] at the [[Century City]] [[Playboy Club]] and was cast in a few television and film roles, Snider had numerous get-rich-quick schemes, including building and selling exercise benches. Stratten helped support Snider financially throughout their short-lived marriage (as he was a Canadian with no working visa, and was not allowed an income within the U.S.).<ref name=\"carpenter\"/> In 1979, Snider formed a partnership with [[Somen Banerjee]] and the attorney Bruce Nahin to form what became the male [[strip club]] format of [[Chippendales]].\n\nIn 1980, Stratten was named ''Playboy''{{'}}s [[List of Playboy Playmates of the Year|Playmate of the Year]] and was cast in a motion picture, ''[[They All Laughed]]'' (1981) directed by [[Peter Bogdanovich]], with whom she began an affair. Stratten and Snider separated and he hired a [[private investigator]] to follow her.\n\n=== Death ===\nOn August 14, 1980, Stratten was shot and killed in the [[West Los Angeles]] house they had shared. Snider's body was found next to hers. Police believed he raped and murdered her, sexually abused the corpse, then killed himself with the same shotgun.<ref name=\"carpenter\"/><ref name=\"Canby\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/11/10/movies/screen-star-80-a-sex-symbol-s-life-and-death.html?pagewanted=all|title=Screen: 'Star 80,' a Sex-Symbol's Life and Death|last=Canby|first=Vincent|work=The New York Times|date=November 10, 1983|accessdate=2 May 2009}}</ref>\n\nSnider's remains are buried at Schara Tzedeck Cemetery in [[New Westminster]], [[British Columbia]], Canada.\n\n== In popular culture ==\nSnider has been portrayed in two films. The first was a made-for-television movie about the murder called ''[[Death of a Centerfold: The Dorothy Stratten Story]]'' (1981), which starred [[Jamie Lee Curtis]] as Stratten and [[Bruce Weitz]] as Snider. [[Bob Fosse]]'s feature film ''[[Star 80]]'' (1983) dramatized Stratten's life and death. [[Mariel Hemingway]] played Stratten and [[Eric Roberts]] portrayed Snider in a highly acclaimed performance.<ref name=\"Canby\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Find a Grave|4176}}\n\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Snider, Paul}}\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:1980 deaths]]\n[[Category:Murder\u2013suicides in California]]\n[[Category:People from Vancouver]]\n[[Category:Suicides by firearm in California]]\n[[Category:Canadian Jews]]\n[[Category:Burials in British Columbia]]\n[[Category:Canadian expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:Canadian murderers]]\n[[Category:Canadian rapists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian criminals]]\n[[Category:Canadian male criminals]]\n[[Category:Necrophiles]]\n", "name_user": "Greyjoy", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Snider"}
{"title_page": "Trick of the Eye", "text_new": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Trick of the Eye\n| image                = \n| image_size           = \n| image_alt            = \n| caption              = \n| genre                = {{hlist|Mystery|Thriller}}\n| based_on             = ''Trick of the Eye'' (novel) by [[Jane Stanton Hitchcock]]\n| writer               = [[John Gay (screenwriter)|John Gay]]<br>[[Ken and Jim Wheat]]\n| director             = Ed Kaplan\n| starring             = [[Ellen Burstyn]]<br>[[Meg Tilly]]<br>[[Paxton Whitehead]]<br>[[Alastair Duncan (actor)|Alastair Duncan]]<br>[[Barnard Hughes]]\n| music                = [[Allyn Ferguson]] \n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| producer             = [[David A. Rosemont]]<br>[[Brent Shields]]\n| executive_producer   = Richard Welsh\n| location             = [[Pasadena, California]]\n| editor               = Sabrina Plisco-Morris\n| cinematography       = [[Shelly Johnson (cinematographer)|Shelly Johnson]]\n| runtime              = 95 minutes\n| company              = Signboard Hill Productions<br>[[Sonar Entertainment|Hallmark Entertainment]]\n| distributor          = [[CBS]]\n| budget               = \n| network              = CBS\n| picture_format       = Color\n| audio_format         = [[Stereophonic sound|Stereo]]\n| first_aired          = {{start date|1994|10|23}}\n| last_aired           = \n| website              = \n}}\n\n'''''Trick of the Eye''''' (also known as '''''Primal Secrets''''') is a 1994 American [[television film|made-for-television]] [[psychological thriller|psychological thriller film]] starring [[Ellen Burstyn]] and [[Meg Tilly]]. Directed by Ed Kaplan, it is based on the 1992 novel of the same name by [[Jane Stanton Hitchcock]]. The film originally premiered on [[CBS]] as a presentation of ''CBS Sunday Afternoon Showcase'' on October 23, 1994.\n\n==Plot==\nFaith Crowell (Meg Tilly) is a struggling bohemian artist who is commissioned to paint a mural for wealthy, reclusive socialite widow Frances Griffin (Ellen Burstyn). Frances wants Faith to paint murals all over the ornate walls of the abandoned ballroom of her ostentatious 211-acre estate. The theme of the mural is to be the grand entrance of Frances' daughter Cassandra at her \"coming out\" fete, which also happens to be the night Cassandra mysteriously died.\n\nFaith soon begins receiving expensive gifts from Frances, which she enjoys but doesn't understand why. Before long, Faith starts picking up on several uncanny resemblances between herself and the dead Cassandra. Eventually, she is invited to live in Frances' mansion until the mural is complete, and she discovers a painting of Cassandra and sees the haunting resemblance.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Ellen Burstyn]] as Frances Griffin\n*[[Meg Tilly]] as Faith Crowell\n*[[Paxton Whitehead]] as Deane\n*[[Alastair Duncan (actor)|Alastair Duncan]] as Simon\n*[[Romy Rosemont]] as Cathy Newman\n*[[Barnard Hughes]] as Harry Pitt\n\n==Production and media releases==\nThe film was shot at [[Huntington Library]] in [[Pasadena, California]] from August 8 to August 31, 1994.\n\nIn July 1995, it was released on [[VHS]] and [[LaserDisc]] under the title ''Primal Secrets'' by [[Crown Media Holdings|Hallmark Home Entertainment]] and [[RLJE Films|Image Entertainment]].\n\n==References==\n#[http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/475633/Trick-of-the-Eye/misc-notes.html Trick of the Eye: Miscellaneous Notes] at [[Turner Classic Movies|TCM]] (1994).\n#[https://people.com/archive/picks-and-pans-review-trick-of-the-eye-vol-42-no-17/ Picks and Pans Review: Trick of the Eye] by ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' magazine (October 24, 1994).\n#[https://www.lddb.com/laserdisc/06525/ID3185HL/Primal-Secrets-(Trick-of-the-Eye) Trick of the Eye] at LaserDisc Database (1995) \n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|0111490|Trick of the Eye}}\n*{{tcmdb title|475633|Trick of the Eye}}\n*{{Amg movie|178294|Trick of the Eye}}\n\n[[Category:1994 films]]\n[[Category:1994 television films]]\n[[Category:1990s psychological thriller films]]\n[[Category:1990s mystery films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American television films]]\n[[Category:American psychological thriller films]]\n[[Category:American mystery films]]\n[[Category:CBS network films]]\n[[Category:Films shot in California]]\n\n{{US-tv-drama-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Trick of the Eye\n| image                = \n| image_size           = \n| image_alt            = \n| caption              = \n| genre                = {{hlist|Mystery|Thriller}}\n| based_on             = ''Trick of the Eye'' (novel) by [[Jane Stanton Hitchcock]]\n| writer               = [[John Gay (screenwriter)|John Gay]]<br>[[Ken and Jim Wheat]]\n| director             = Ed Kaplan\n| starring             = [[Ellen Burstyn]]<br>[[Meg Tilly]]<br>[[Paxton Whitehead]]<br>[[Alastair Duncan (actor)|Alastair Duncan]]<br>[[Barnard Hughes]]\n| music                = [[Allyn Ferguson]] \n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| producer             = [[David A. Rosemont]]<br>[[Brent Shields]]\n| executive_producer   = Richard Welsh\n| location             = [[Pasadena, California]]\n| editor               = Sabrina Plisco-Morris\n| cinematography       = [[Shelly Johnson (cinematographer)|Shelly Johnson]]\n| runtime              = 95 minutes\n| company              = Signboard Hill Productions<br>[[Sonar Entertainment|Hallmark Entertainment]]\n| distributor          = [[CBS]]\n| budget               = \n| network              = CBS\n| picture_format       = Color\n| audio_format         = [[Stereophonic sound|Stereo]]\n| first_aired          = {{start date|1994|10|23}}\n| last_aired           = \n| website              = \n}}\n\n'''''Trick of the Eye''''' (also known as '''''Primal Secrets''''') is a 1994 American [[television film|made-for-television]] [[psychological thriller|psychological thriller film]] starring [[Ellen Burstyn]] and [[Meg Tilly]]. Directed by Ed Kaplan, it is based on the 1992 novel of the same name by [[Jane Stanton Hitchcock]]. The film originally premiered on [[CBS]] as a presentation of ''CBS Sunday Afternoon Showcase'' on October 23, 1994.\n\n==Plot==\nFaith Crowell (Meg Tilly) is a struggling bohemian artist who is commissioned to paint a mural for wealthy, reclusive socialite widow Frances Griffin (Ellen Burstyn). Frances wants Faith to paint murals all over the ornate walls of the abandoned ballroom of her ostentatious 211-acre estate. The theme of the mural is to be the grand entrance of Frances' daughter Cassandra at her \"coming out\" fete, which also happens to be the night Cassandra mysteriously died.\n\nFaith soon begins receiving expensive gifts from Frances, which she enjoys but doesn't understand why. Before long, Faith starts picking up on several uncanny resemblances between herself and the dead Cassandra. Eventually, Faith is invited to live in Frances' mansion until the mural is complete, and she discovers a painting of Cassandra and sees the haunting resemblance.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Ellen Burstyn]] as Frances Griffin\n*[[Meg Tilly]] as Faith Crowell\n*[[Paxton Whitehead]] as Deane\n*[[Alastair Duncan (actor)|Alastair Duncan]] as Simon\n*[[Romy Rosemont]] as Cathy Newman\n*[[Barnard Hughes]] as Harry Pitt\n\n==Production and media releases==\nThe film was shot at [[Huntington Library]] in [[Pasadena, California]] from August 8 to August 31, 1994.\n\nIn July 1995, it was released on [[VHS]] and [[LaserDisc]] under the title ''Primal Secrets'' by [[Crown Media Holdings|Hallmark Home Entertainment]] and [[RLJE Films|Image Entertainment]].\n\n==References==\n#[http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/475633/Trick-of-the-Eye/misc-notes.html Trick of the Eye: Miscellaneous Notes] at [[Turner Classic Movies|TCM]] (1994).\n#[https://people.com/archive/picks-and-pans-review-trick-of-the-eye-vol-42-no-17/ Picks and Pans Review: Trick of the Eye] by ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' magazine (October 24, 1994).\n#[https://www.lddb.com/laserdisc/06525/ID3185HL/Primal-Secrets-(Trick-of-the-Eye) Trick of the Eye] at LaserDisc Database (1995) \n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|0111490|Trick of the Eye}}\n*{{tcmdb title|475633|Trick of the Eye}}\n*{{Amg movie|178294|Trick of the Eye}}\n\n[[Category:1994 films]]\n[[Category:1994 television films]]\n[[Category:1990s psychological thriller films]]\n[[Category:1990s mystery films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American television films]]\n[[Category:American psychological thriller films]]\n[[Category:American mystery films]]\n[[Category:CBS network films]]\n[[Category:Films shot in California]]\n\n{{US-tv-drama-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePlot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trick_of_the_Eye"}
{"title_page": "1847", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2011}}\n{{Year dab|1847}}\n{{Year nav|1847}}\n{{C19 year in topic}}{{Year article header|1847}}\n\n== Events ==\n\n=== January&ndash;March ===\n* [[January 4]] &ndash; [[Samuel Colt]] sells his first [[revolver]] pistol to the U.S government.\n* [[January 13]] &ndash; The [[Treaty of Cahuenga]] ends fighting in the [[Mexican\u2013American War]] in [[California]].\n* [[January 16]] &ndash; [[John C. Fr\u00e9mont]] is appointed Governor of the new [[California]] Territory.\n* [[January 17]] &ndash; [[St. Anthony Hall]] fraternity is founded at [[Columbia University]], New York City.\n* [[January 30]] &ndash; [[Yerba Buena, California]] is renamed [[San Francisco]].\n* [[February 5]] &ndash; A rescue effort, called the First Relief, leaves Johnson's Ranch to save the ill-fated [[Donner Party]] (California-bound emigrants who became snowbound in the Sierra Nevada earlier this winter; some have resorted to survival cannibalism).\n* [[February 22]] &ndash; [[Mexican\u2013American War]]: [[Battle of Buena Vista]] &ndash; 5,000 American troops under General [[Zachary Taylor]] use their superiority in [[artillery]] to drive off 15,000 Mexican troops under [[Antonio L\u00f3pez de Santa Anna]], defeating the Mexicans the next day.\n* [[February 25]] &ndash; [[State University of Iowa]] is founded in [[Iowa City, Iowa]].\n* [[March]] &ndash; First known publication of the classic joke \"[[Why did the chicken cross the road?]]\", in ''[[The Knickerbocker|The Knickerbocker, or New-York Monthly Magazine]]''.\n* [[March 1]]\n** The state of [[Michigan]] formally abolishes the [[death penalty]].\n** [[Faustin Soulouque]] is elected President of [[Haiti]].\n* [[March 4]] &ndash; The [[30th United States Congress]] is sworn into office.\n* [[March 9]] &ndash; [[Mexican\u2013American War]]: United States forces under General [[Winfield Scott]] invade Mexico near [[Veracruz (city)|Veracruz]].\n* [[March 14]] &ndash; [[Verdi]]'s opera ''[[Macbeth (opera)|Macbeth]]'' premieres at the [[Teatro della Pergola]], in [[Florence]], Italy.\n* [[March 29]] &ndash; [[Mexican\u2013American War]]: United States forces under General [[Winfield Scott]] take [[Veracruz (city)|Veracruz]] after a [[siege]].\n\n=== April&ndash;June ===\n* [[April 5]] &ndash; The world's first municipally-funded civic public [[park]], [[Birkenhead Park]] in [[Birkenhead]] on [[Merseyside]], England, is opened.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wirral.gov.uk/LGCL/100006/200073/670/content_0001110.html |title=The History of Birkenhead Park |accessdate=2007-09-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080626164507/http://www.wirral.gov.uk/LGCL/100006/200073/670/content_0001110.html |archivedate=June 26, 2008 }}</ref>\n* [[April 15]] &ndash; [[The Lawrence School, Sanawar]] is established in India.\n* [[April 16]] &ndash; [[New Zealand Wars]]: A minor [[M\u0101ori people|M\u0101ori]] chief is accidentally shot by a junior [[British Army]] officer in [[Whanganui]] on [[New Zealand]]'s [[North Island]], triggering the [[Wanganui Campaign]] (which continues until [[July 23]]).\n* [[April 25]] &ndash; The [[Exmouth (brig)|brig ''Exmouth'']], carrying Irish emigrants from [[Derry]] bound for [[Quebec]], is wrecked off [[Islay]], with only three survivors from more than 250 on board.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Exmouth - a terrible tragedy on Islay|url=http://www.islayinfo.com/exmouth-islay-tragedy.html|work=Isle of Islay|year=2011|accessdate=2012-07-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Exmouth shipwreck off the Antrim Coast, Northern Ireland|url=http://www.my-secret-northern-ireland.com/the-exmouth.html|work=My Secret Northern Ireland|accessdate=2012-07-13}}</ref>\n* [[May]] &ndash; The [[Architectural Association School of Architecture]] is founded in London.\n* [[May 7]] &ndash; In [[Philadelphia]], the [[American Medical Association]] (AMA) is founded.\n* [[May 8]] &ndash; The [[1847 Nagano earthquake|Nagano earthquake]] leaves more than 8,600 people dead in [[Japan]].\n* [[May 31]] &ndash; Second [[Treaties of Erzurum|Treaty of Erzurum]]: the [[Ottoman Empire]] cedes [[Abadan Island]] to the [[Qajar dynasty|Persian Empire]].\n* [[June]] &ndash; E.H. Booth & Co. Ltd, which becomes the northern England supermarket chain [[Booths]], is founded when tea dealer Edwin Henry Booth, 19, opens a shop called \"The China House\" in [[Blackpool]].\n* [[June 1]] &ndash; The first congress of the [[Communist League]] is held in London.\n* [[June 26]] &ndash; The first passenger railway wholly within modern-day Denmark opens, from [[Copenhagen]] to [[Roskilde]].<ref>{{Marshall-GuinnessRail}}</ref>{{page needed|date=October 2016}}\n\n=== July\u2013September ===\n* [[July 1]] &ndash; The United States issues its first [[postage stamp]]s ''(pictured)''.[[File:First US Stamps 1847 Issue.jpg|thumb|300px|<center>The first U.S. postage stamps have portraits of [[Benjamin Franklin]] and [[George Washington]]. Though highly collectable, they are far from being the most valuable.</center>]]\n* [[July 24]] &ndash; After 17 months of travel, [[Brigham Young]] leads 148 [[Mormon pioneers]] into [[Salt Lake Valley]], resulting in the establishment of [[Salt Lake City]].\n* [[July 26]] &ndash; [[Liberia]] gains independence.\n* [[July 29]] &ndash; The [[Cumberland School of Law]] is founded at [[Cumberland University]], in [[Lebanon, Tennessee]]. At the end of this year, only 15 law schools exist in the United States.\n* [[August 12]] &ndash; [[Mexican\u2013American War]]: U.S. troops of General [[Winfield Scott]] begin to advance along the [[aqueduct (water supply)|aqueduct]] around Lakes [[Lake Chalco|Chalco]] and [[Lake Xochimilco|Xochimilco]] in Mexico.\n* [[August 20]] &ndash; [[Mexican\u2013American War]] &ndash; [[Battle of Churubusco]]: U.S. troops defeat Mexican forces.\n* [[August]] &ndash; [[Yale Corporation]] establishes the first graduate school in the United States, as ''Department of Philosophy and the Arts'' (renamed ''Graduate School of Arts and Sciences'' in [[1892]]).\n* [[September 14]] &ndash; [[Mexican\u2013American War]]: U.S. general [[Winfield Scott]] [[Battle for Mexico City|enters Mexico City]], marking the end of organized Mexican resistance.\n* [[September 30]] &ndash; The [[Vegetarian Society]] is formed in the United Kingdom (it remains the oldest in the world).\n\n=== October&ndash;December ===\n* [[October]] &ndash; The last [[volcanic eruption]] of [[Mount Guntur]] in [[West Java]] occurs.\n* [[October 12]] &ndash; German inventors and industrialists [[Werner von Siemens]] and [[Johann Georg Halske]] found [[Siemens & Halske]] to develop the [[electrical telegraph]].\n* [[October 19]] &ndash; [[Charlotte Bront\u00eb]] publishes ''[[Jane Eyre]]'' under the pen name of Currer Bell in England.\n* [[October 31]] &ndash; [[Theta Delta Chi]] is founded as a social [[Fraternities and sororities|fraternity]] at [[Union College]], [[Schenectady, New York]].\n* [[November 3]]&ndash;[[November 29|29]] &ndash; [[Sonderbund War]]: In Switzerland, General [[Guillaume-Henri Dufour]]'s Federal Army defeats the ''Sonderbund'' (an alliance of seven [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] [[Cantons of Switzerland|cantons]]) in a civil war, with a total of only 86 deaths.\n* [[November 4]]&ndash;[[November 8|8]] &ndash; [[James Young Simpson]] discovers the [[anesthetic]] properties of [[chloroform]] and first uses it, successfully, on a patient, in an [[obstetric]] case in [[Edinburgh]].<ref>First communicated to the Medico-Chirurgical Society of Edinburgh, November 10, and published in a pamphlet, ''Notice of a New An\u00e6sthetic Agent'', in Edinburgh, November 12.</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Gordon|first=H. Laing|title=Sir James Young Simpson and Chloroform (1811\u20131870)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pYer05UwKBYC&ph=PA108|accessdate=2011-11-11|year=2002|publisher=Minerva Group, Inc|isbn=978-1-4102-0291-8}}</ref>\n* [[November 10]] &ndash; The first brew of [[Carlsberg Group|Carlsberg]] [[beer]] is finished in [[Copenhagen]].\n*  [[November 17]] &ndash; The Battle of Um Swayya Spring takes place near a spring in Qatar, after a Bahraini force under Shaikh Ali bin Khalifa Deputy Ruler of Bahrain defeats the Al Binali tribe. The chief of the Al Binali, Isa bin Tureef, is slain in battle with over 70 fatalities from his side. The battle secured the position of Shaikh Mohamed bin Khalifa\u2019s authority over the entire Qatar peninsula and is a setback for the rival branch Al Abdulla which relocated and separated earlier in the 1840s from Bahrain.\n* [[December 14]] &ndash; [[Emily Bront\u00eb]] and [[Anne Bront\u00eb]] publish ''[[Wuthering Heights]]'' and ''[[Agnes Grey]]'', respectively, in a 3-volume set under the pen names of Ellis Bell and Acton Bell in England.\n* [[December 21]] &ndash; [[Emir Abdelkader]] surrenders to the French in Algeria.\n\n=== Date unknown ===\n* The [[Great Famine (Ireland)|Great Famine]] continues in Ireland. \n* The [[North Carolina General Assembly]] incorporates the railroad town of [[Goldsboro, North Carolina|Goldsborough]], and the [[Wayne County, North Carolina|Wayne]] county seat is moved to the new town.\n* [[Radley College]], an [[English public school]], is founded near Oxford.\n* [[Welfare in Sweden]] takes its first step with the introduction of the ''[[1847 \u00e5rs fattigv\u00e5rdf\u00f6rordning]]''.\n\n== Births ==\n\n=== January ===\n* [[January 5]] &ndash; [[Oku Yasukata]], Japanese field marshal, leading figure in the early Imperial Japanese Army (d. [[1930]])\n* [[January 7]] &ndash; [[Caspar F. Goodrich]], American admiral (d. [[1925]])\n* [[January 24]] &ndash; [[Radomir Putnik]], Serbian field marshal (d. [[1917]])\n* [[January 27]] &ndash; [[Ella Maria Dietz Clymer]], American actress and author (d. [[1920]])\n* [[January 28]] &ndash; [[Dorus Rijkers]], Dutch naval hero (d. [[1928]])\n\n=== February ===\n* [[February 3]] &ndash; [[Warington Baden-Powell]], British admiralty lawyer (d. [[1921]])\n* [[February 5]] &ndash; [[Jo\u00e3o Maria Correia Ayres de Campos, 1st Count of Ameal]], Portuguese politician and antiquarian (d. [[1920]])\n* [[February 8]] &ndash; [[Hugh Price Hughes]], Methodist social reformer, first Superintendent of the [[West London Mission]] (d. [[1902]])\n* [[February 11]] &ndash; [[Thomas Alva Edison]], American inventor (d. [[1931]])\n* [[February 13]] &ndash; [[Sir Robert McAlpine, 1st Baronet|Sir Robert McAlpine]], Scottish builder (d. [[1930]])\n* [[February 15]] &ndash; [[Robert Fuchs]], Austrian composer (d. [[1927]])\n* [[February 16]] &ndash; [[Philipp Scharwenka]], Polish-German composer (d. [[1917]])\n* [[February 17]] &ndash; [[Otto Blehr]], Norwegian attorney, Liberal Party politician, 7th [[Prime Minister of Norway]] (d. [[1927]])\n\n=== March ===\n* [[March 1]] &ndash; [[Thomas Brock|Sir Thomas Brock]], English sculptor (d. [[1922]])\n* [[March 2]]\n** [[Isaac Barr]], Anglican clergyman, promoter of British colonial settlement schemes (d. [[1937]])\n** [[Cayetano Arellano]], first Chief Justice of the Supreme Court of the Philippines under the American Civil Government (d. [[1920]])\n* [[March 3]] &ndash; [[Alexander Graham Bell]], Scottish-born American inventor (d. [[1922]])\n* [[March 4]] &ndash; [[Carl Josef Bayer]], Austrian chemist (d. [[1904]])\n* [[March 14]] &ndash; [[Castro Alves]], Brazilian poet (d. [[1871]])\n* [[March 18]] &ndash; [[William O'Connell Bradley]], American politician from Kentucky (d. [[1914]])\n* [[March 23]] &ndash; [[Edmund Gurney]], British psychologist (d. [[1888]])\n* [[March 27]]\n** [[Otto Wallach]], German chemist, [[Nobel Prize]] laureate (d. [[1931]])\n** [[Garret Barry (piper)|Garret Barry]], Irish musician (d. [[1899]])\n\n=== April ===\n* [[April 2]] &ndash; [[Charles Frederic Moberly Bell]], British journalist, editor (d. [[1911]])\n* [[April 10]] &ndash; [[Joseph Pulitzer]], Hungarian-born journalist, newspaper publisher (d. [[1911]])\n* [[April 15]] &ndash; [[Yehudah Aryeh Leib Alter]], Polish Hasidic rabbi (d. [[1905]])\n* [[April 27]] &ndash; [[Emma Irene \u00c5str\u00f6m]], Finnish teacher, Finland's first female university graduate (d. [[1934]]\n\n=== May ===\n* [[May 7]] &ndash; [[Archibald Primrose, 5th Earl of Rosebery]], [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]] (d. [[1929]])\n* [[May 14]] &ndash; [[Frederick William Borden|Sir Frederick William Borden]], Canadian politician (d. [[1917]])\n\n=== June ===\n* [[June 8]]\n** [[Oleksander Barvinsky]], Ukrainian politician (d. [[1926]])\n** [[Ida Saxton McKinley]], [[First Lady of the United States]] (d. [[1907]])\n* [[June 10]] &ndash; [[Gina Krog]], Norwegian suffragist (d. [[1916]])\n* [[June 11]] &ndash; [[Millicent Fawcett|Dame Milicent Fawcett]], British suffragist (d. [[1929]])\n* [[June 16]] &ndash; [[Luella Dowd Smith]], American educator, author, and reformer (d. [[1941]])\n\n=== July ===\n[[File:President Hindenburg.jpg|thumb|right|110px|[[Paul von Hindenburg]]]]\n[[File:Bram Stoker 1906.jpg|thumb|right|110px|[[Bram Stoker]]]] \n* [[July 2]] &ndash; [[Marcel Alexandre Bertrand]], French geologist (d. [[1907]])\n* [[July 9]] &ndash; [[Wong Fei-hung]], Chinese healer, revolutionary (d. [[1925]])\n* [[July 19]] &ndash; [[Alexander Meyrick Broadley]], British historian (d. [[1916]])\n* [[July 20]]\n** [[Lord William Beresford]], Irish army officer, Victoria Cross recipient (d. [[1900]])\n** [[Max Liebermann]], German painter, printmaker (d. [[1935]])\n* [[July 25]] &ndash; [[Paul Langerhans]], German pathologist, biologist (d. [[1888]])\n\n=== August ===\n* [[August 3]] &ndash; [[John Hamilton-Gordon, 1st Marquess of Aberdeen and Temair]], Canadian politician, Governor General (d. [[1934]])\n* [[August 21]] &ndash; [[Hale Johnson]], [[American temperance movement]] leader (d. [[1902]])\n\n=== September ===\n* [[September 1]] &ndash; [[Archibald Kennedy, 3rd Marquess of Ailsa]] (d. [[1938]])\n* [[September 3]] &ndash; [[Charles Stillman Sperry]], American admiral (d. [[1911]])\n* [[September 5]]\n** [[Jesse James]], American outlaw (d. [[1882]])\n** [[Joseph Bucklin Bishop]], American journalist, publisher (d. [[1928]])\n* [[September 10]] &ndash; [[Franklin Bartlett]], American politician (d. [[1909]])\n* [[September 14]] &ndash; [[William Edward Ayrton]], English physicist, electrical engineer (d. [[1908]])\n* [[September 15]] &ndash; [[Tadeusz Browicz]], Polish pathologist (d. [[1928]])\n* [[September 16]] &ndash; [[Arthur Bromley]], British Royal Navy officer who became Admiral Superintendent of Malta Dockyard (d. [[1909]])\n* [[September 17]] &ndash; [[John I. Beggs]], American businessman (d. [[1925]])\n* [[September 22]] &ndash; [[Enrique Almaraz y Santos]], Spanish Catholic cardinal (d. [[1922]])\n* [[September 23]] &ndash; [[Anandamohan Bose]], Indian politician, academic and social reformer (d. [[1906]])\n* [[September 24]] &ndash; [[William Edward Briggs]], British politician (d. [[1903]])\n* [[September 25]] &ndash; [[Edward Austin (cricketer)]], English cricketer (d. [[1891]])\n* [[September 26]] &ndash; [[Wolf Wilhelm Friedrich von Baudissin]], German theologian (d. [[1926]])\n* [[September 30]]\n** [[Wilhelmina Drucker]], Dutch feminist (d. [[1925]])\n** [[Vilma Hugonnai]], Hungarian medical doctor (d. [[1922]])\n\n=== October ===\n[[File:Thomas F. Porter.png|thumb|110px|[[Thomas F. Porter]]]]\n* [[October 1]]\n** [[Sophia Amirajibi]], Georgian translator of poetry (d. [[1906]])\n** [[Annie Besant]], English women's rights activist, writer and orator (d. [[1933]])\n* [[October 2]] &ndash; [[Paul von Hindenburg]], German field marshal, [[President of Germany]] (d. [[1934]])\n* [[October 3]] &ndash; [[Lilian Whiting]], American journalist, editor, and author (d. [[1942]])\n* [[October 4]] &ndash; [[Louis Henri Boussenard]], French author of adventure novels (d. [[1911]])\n* [[October 6]] &ndash; [[Webb C. Ball]], American jeweler, watchmaker from Fredericktown, Ohio (d. [[1922]])\n* [[October 9]] &ndash; [[William Anderson Black]], Canadian politician (d. [[1934]])\n* [[October 11]] &ndash; [[Alexander Bolton]], Australian politician (d. [[1918]])\n* [[October 13]]\n** [[Sir Arthur Dyke Acland, 13th Baronet]], British politician (d. [[1926]])\n** [[Maurice Bailloud]], French general (d. [[1921]])\n* [[October 14]] &ndash; [[Wilgelm Vitgeft]], Russian admiral (d. [[1904]])\n* [[October 15]] &ndash; [[Ralph Albert Blakelock]], American romanticist painter (d. [[1919]])\n* [[October 16]] &ndash; [[Gustav Baron]], Croatian theologian (d. [[1914]])\n* [[October 17]]\n** [[Jervoise Athelstane Baines]], Indian civil servant (d. [[1925]])\n** [[Chiquinha Gonzaga]], Brazilian composer (d. [[1935]])\n* [[October 18]] &ndash; [[Emma Elizabeth Brown]], American author and artist (unknown year of death)\n* [[October 19]] &ndash; [[Aurilla Furber]], American author, editor, and activist  (d. [[1898]])\n* [[October 20]] &ndash; [[Mifflin E. Bell]], American architect (d. [[1904]])\n* [[October 21]] &ndash; [[Edvard Brandes]], Danish politician (d. [[1931]])\n* [[October 22]] &ndash; [[Koos de la Rey]], Boer general (d. [[1914]])\n* [[October 23]] &ndash; [[Gottfried Blocklinger]], United States admiral (d. [[1930]])\n* [[October 24]] &ndash; [[John Winfield Bonser]], British colonial judge (d. [[1914]])\n* [[October 27]] &ndash; [[George Armitstead (mayor)]], Latvian politician (d. [[1912]])\n* [[October 30]]\n** [[Charlie Bassett]], American sheriff (d. [[1896]])\n** [[Thomas F. Porter]], American politician, 32nd [[Mayor of Lynn, Massachusetts]] (d. [[1927]])\n* [[October 31]] &ndash; [[Wendell P. Bowman]], American military officer (d. [[1928]])\n\n=== November ===\n* [[November 1]] &ndash; [[Emma Albani]], Canandian operatic soprano (d. [[1930]])\n* [[November 2]] &ndash; [[Georges Sorel]], French socialist (d. [[1922]])\n* [[November 3]] &ndash; [[George Thomas Baird]], Canadian politician (d. [[1917]])\n* [[November 4]]\n** [[Infante Augusto, Duke of Coimbra]], Royal prince of Portugal (d. [[1889]])\n** [[William Allen (Congregationalist)]], English-born Australian Congregational clergyman (d. [[1919]])\n* [[November 6]] &ndash; [[Ugo Balzani]], Italian historian (d. [[1916]])\n* [[November 7]]\n** [[Melvin O. Adams]], American attorney, businessman (d. [[1920]])\n** [[Lotta Crabtree]], American stage actress (d. [[1924]])\n* [[November 8]]\n** [[Jean Casimir-Perier]], 6th President of France (d. [[1907]])\n** [[Bram Stoker]], Irish author of the [[Gothic fiction|Gothic]] novel ''[[Dracula]]'' (d. [[1912]])\n** [[Charles Alexander (cricketer, born 1847)]], English cricketer (d. [[1902]])\n* [[November 9]] &ndash; [[Carl Wilhelm B\u00f8ckmann Barth]], Norwegian artist (d. [[1919]])\n* [[November 10]] &ndash; [[Frederick Arthur Bridgman]], American artist (d. [[1928]])\n* [[November 11]]\n** [[Otto B\u00f6hler]], Austrian silhouette-artist (d. [[1911]])\n** [[Adam Carr Bell]], Canadian politician (d. [[1912]])\n* [[November 19]] &ndash; [[Carl Friedl\u00e4nder]], German pathologist, microbiologist (d. [[1887]])\n* [[November 23]]\n** [[Joseph Ackroyd]], American politician (d. [[1915]])\n** [[Walter Biggar Blaikie]], British astronomer, engineer, historian and printer (d. [[1928]])\n* [[November 25]] &ndash; [[George W. Anson]], British actor (d. [[1920]])\n* [[November 26]] &ndash; [[Maria Feodorovna (Dagmar of Denmark)|Dagmar of Denmark]], empress of Tsar [[Alexander III of Russia]] (d. [[1928]])\n* [[November 30]] &ndash; [[Afonso Pena]], Brazilian president (d. [[1909]])\n\n=== December ===\n* [[December 1]] &ndash; [[Agathe Backer-Gr\u00f8ndahl]], Norwegian pianist, composer (d. [[1907]])\n* [[December 3]] &ndash; [[Arthur Ivan Allin]], Danish musician (d. [[1926]])\n* [[December 5]] &ndash; [[Francis Baker (cricketer)]], English cricketer (d. [[1901]])\n* [[December 6]] &ndash; [[John Elmes Beale]], British politician (d. [[1928]])\n* [[December 7]] &ndash; [[George Grossmith]], English actor, comic writer (d. [[1912]])\n* [[December 10]]\n** [[John M. Baillie]], Canadian politician (d. [[1913]])\n** [[Harry Boyle (cricketer)|Harry Boyle]], leading Australian Test cricketer of the late 1870s and early 1880s (d. [[1907]])\n* [[December 15]] &ndash; [[Rolf Andvord (consul)]], Norwegian shipowner (d. [[1906]])\n* [[December 18]]\n** [[Sir William Acland, 2nd Baronet]], British Royal Navy admiral (d. [[1924]])\n** [[Augusta Holm\u00e8s]], French composer (d. [[1903]])\n* [[December 17]]\n** [[\u00c9mile Faguet]], French writer, critic (d. [[1916]])\n** [[Michel-Joseph Maunoury]], French general during [[World War I]] (d. [[1923]])\n* [[December 20]] &ndash; [[Ferenc Bihar]], Hungarian politician (d. [[1920]])\n* [[December 21]] &ndash; [[Fletcher S. Bassett]], American founder of the Chicago Folk-Lore Society (d. [[1893]])\n* [[December 27]] &ndash; [[Ferdinand Begg]], Scottish stockbroker, politician (d. [[1926]])\n* [[December 28]] &ndash; [[Giuseppe Maria Giulietti]], Italian explorer (d. [[1881]])\n* [[December 29]]\n** [[Alexis-Xyste Bernard]], Canadian Catholic bishop (d. [[1923]])\n** [[Sergey Andreyevsky]], Russian writer, poet, literary critic and lawyer (d. [[1918]])\n* [[December 30]] &ndash; [[John Peter Altgeld]], American politician, 20th Governor of Illinois (d. [[1902]])\n* [[December 31]] &ndash; [[Wilson S. Bissell]], American politician from New York (d. [[1903]])\n\n=== Date unknown ===\n* [[Eunice Eloisae Gibbs Allyn]], American correspondent, author, and songwriter (d. [[1916]])\n* [[Band\u014d Kakitsu I]], Japanese [[kabuki]] actor (d. [[1893]])\n* [[Clarissa Caldwell Lathrop]], American social reformer and autobiographer (d. [[1892]])\n\n== Deaths ==\n\n=== January&ndash;June ===\n[[File:Fanny Hensel 1842.jpg|thumb|right|110px|[[Fanny Mendelssohn]]]]\n* [[January 19]] &ndash; [[Charles Bent]], first Governor of New Mexico Territory (b. [[1799]]) (assassinated)\n* [[February 3]] &ndash; [[Marie Duplessis]], French courtesan (b. [[1824]])\n* [[March 9]] &ndash; [[Mary Anning]], British paleontologist (b. [[1799]])\n* [[April 21]] &ndash; [[Barbara Spooner Wilberforce]], wife of British abolitionist William Wilberforce (b. [[1777]])\n* [[April 30]] &ndash; [[Archduke Charles, Duke of Teschen|Archduke Charles of Austria]], Austrian general (b. [[1771]])\n* [[May 14]] &ndash; [[Fanny Mendelssohn]], German composer, pianist (b. [[1805]])\n* [[May 15]] &ndash; [[Daniel O'Connell]], Irish politician who promoted the [[Roman Catholic Relief Act 1829]] (b. [[1775]])\n* [[May 16]] &ndash; [[Vicente Rocafuerte]], 2nd President of Ecuador (b. [[1783]])\n* [[May 29]] &ndash; [[Emmanuel de Grouchy, Marquis de Grouchy]], French marshal (b. [[1766]])\n* [[May 31]] &ndash; [[Abbasgulu Bakikhanov]], Azerbaijani writer (b. [[1794]])\n* [[June 11]] &ndash; [[John Franklin|Sir John Franklin]], British explorer (b. [[1786]])\n\n=== July&ndash;December ===\n[[File:Mendelssohn Bartholdy.jpg|thumb|110px|right|110px|[[Felix Mendelssohn]]]]\n* [[July 7]] &ndash; [[Thomas Carpenter (glassmaker)|Thomas Carpenter]], American glassmaker (b. [[1752]])\n* [[July 16]] &ndash; [[Karl Friedrich Burdach]], German physiologist (b. [[1776]])\n* [[September 4]] &ndash; [[Franti\u0161ek Vladislav Hek]], Czech patriot (b. [[1769]])\n* [[September 13]] &ndash; [[Nicolas Oudinot]], French marshal (b. [[1767]])\n* [[October 3]] &ndash; [[Charles Hatchett]], English chemist (b. [[1765]])\n* [[October 22]] \n** [[Henriette Herz]], German salonni\u00e9re (b. [[1764]])\n** Negus [[Sahle Selassie]] of [[Shewa]] (b. c. [[1795]])\n* [[November 4]] &ndash; [[Felix Mendelssohn]], German composer (b. [[1809]])\n* [[December 14]]\n** [[Manuel Jos\u00e9 Arce]], Central American politician (b. [[1787]])\n** [[Dorothy Ann Thrupp]], British psalmist (b. [[1779]])\n* Unknown: [[Jeanne Genevi\u00e8ve Labrosse]], French balloonist and parachutist (b. [[1775]])\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n* [http://www.familytales.org/results.php?year=1847 Historic Letters of 1847]\n[[Turtle Bunbury]], \u20181847 \u2013 A Chronicle of Genius, Generosity & Savagery,\u2019 (Gill, 2016). {{ISBN|9780717168347}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1847}}\n[[Category:1847| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2011}}\n{{Year dab|1847}}\n{{Year nav|1847}}\n{{C19 year in topic}}{{Year article header|1847}}\n\n== Events ==\n\n=== January&ndash;March ===\n* [[January 4]] &ndash; [[Samuel Colt]] sells his first [[revolver]] pistol to the U.S government.\n* [[January 13]] &ndash; The [[Treaty of Cahuenga]] ends fighting in the [[Mexican\u2013American War]] in [[California]].\n* [[January 16]] &ndash; [[John C. Fr\u00e9mont]] is appointed Governor of the new [[California]] Territory.\n* [[January 17]] &ndash; [[St. Anthony Hall]] fraternity is founded at [[Columbia University]], New York City.\n* [[January 30]] &ndash; [[Yerba Buena, California]] is renamed [[San Francisco]].\n* [[February 5]] &ndash; A rescue effort, called the First Relief, leaves Johnson's Ranch to save the ill-fated [[Donner Party]] (California-bound emigrants who became snowbound in the Sierra Nevada earlier this winter; some have resorted to survival cannibalism).\n* [[February 22]] &ndash; [[Mexican\u2013American War]]: [[Battle of Buena Vista]] &ndash; 5,000 American troops under General [[Zachary Taylor]] use their superiority in [[artillery]] to drive off 15,000 Mexican troops under [[Antonio L\u00f3pez de Santa Anna]], defeating the Mexicans the next day.\n* [[February 25]] &ndash; [[State University of Iowa]] is founded in [[Iowa City, Iowa]].\n* [[March]] &ndash; First known publication of the classic joke \"[[Why did the chicken cross the road?]]\", in ''[[The Knickerbocker|The Knickerbocker, or New-York Monthly Magazine]]''.\n* [[March 1]]\n** The state of [[Michigan]] formally abolishes the [[death penalty]].\n** [[Faustin Soulouque]] is elected President of [[Haiti]].\n* [[March 4]] &ndash; The [[30th United States Congress]] is sworn into office.\n* [[March 9]] &ndash; [[Mexican\u2013American War]]: United States forces under General [[Winfield Scott]] invade Mexico near [[Veracruz (city)|Veracruz]].\n* [[March 14]] &ndash; [[Verdi]]'s opera ''[[Macbeth (opera)|Macbeth]]'' premieres at the [[Teatro della Pergola]], in [[Florence]], Italy.\n* [[March 29]] &ndash; [[Mexican\u2013American War]]: United States forces under General [[Winfield Scott]] take [[Veracruz (city)|Veracruz]] after a [[siege]].\n\n=== April&ndash;June ===\n* [[April 5]] &ndash; The world's first municipally-funded civic public [[park]], [[Birkenhead Park]] in [[Birkenhead]] on [[Merseyside]], England, is opened.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wirral.gov.uk/LGCL/100006/200073/670/content_0001110.html |title=The History of Birkenhead Park |accessdate=2007-09-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080626164507/http://www.wirral.gov.uk/LGCL/100006/200073/670/content_0001110.html |archivedate=June 26, 2008 }}</ref>\n* [[April 15]] &ndash; [[The Lawrence School, Sanawar]] is established in India.\n* [[April 16]] &ndash; [[New Zealand Wars]]: A minor [[M\u0101ori people|M\u0101ori]] chief is accidentally shot by a junior [[British Army]] officer in [[Whanganui]] on [[New Zealand]]'s [[North Island]], triggering the [[Wanganui Campaign]] (which continues until [[July 23]]).\n* [[April 25]] &ndash; The [[Exmouth (brig)|brig ''Exmouth'']], carrying Irish emigrants from [[Derry]] bound for [[Quebec]], is wrecked off [[Islay]], with only three survivors from more than 250 on board.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Exmouth - a terrible tragedy on Islay|url=http://www.islayinfo.com/exmouth-islay-tragedy.html|work=Isle of Islay|year=2011|accessdate=2012-07-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Exmouth shipwreck off the Antrim Coast, Northern Ireland|url=http://www.my-secret-northern-ireland.com/the-exmouth.html|work=My Secret Northern Ireland|accessdate=2012-07-13}}</ref>\n* [[May]] &ndash; The [[Architectural Association School of Architecture]] is founded in London.\n* [[May 7]] &ndash; In [[Philadelphia]], the [[American Medical Association]] (AMA) is founded.\n* [[May 8]] &ndash; The [[1847 Nagano earthquake|Nagano earthquake]] leaves more than 8,600 people dead in [[Japan]].\n* [[May 31]] &ndash; Second [[Treaties of Erzurum|Treaty of Erzurum]]: the [[Ottoman Empire]] cedes [[Abadan Island]] to the [[Qajar dynasty|Persian Empire]].\n* [[June]] &ndash; E.H. Booth & Co. Ltd, which becomes the northern England supermarket chain [[Booths]], is founded when tea dealer Edwin Henry Booth, 19, opens a shop called \"The China House\" in [[Blackpool]].\n* [[June 1]] &ndash; The first congress of the [[Communist League]] is held in London.\n* [[June 26]] &ndash; The first passenger railway wholly within modern-day Denmark opens, from [[Copenhagen]] to [[Roskilde]].<ref>{{Marshall-GuinnessRail}}</ref>{{page needed|date=October 2016}}\n\n=== July\u2013September ===\n* [[July 1]] &ndash; The United States issues its first [[postage stamp]]s ''(pictured)''.[[File:First US Stamps 1847 Issue.jpg|thumb|300px|<center>The first U.S. postage stamps have portraits of [[Benjamin Franklin]] and [[George Washington]]. Though highly collectable, they are far from being the most valuable.</center>]]\n* [[July 24]] &ndash; After 17 months of travel, [[Brigham Young]] leads 148 [[Mormon pioneers]] into [[Salt Lake Valley]], resulting in the establishment of [[Salt Lake City]].\n* [[July 26]] &ndash; [[Liberia]] gains independence.\n* [[July 29]] &ndash; The [[Cumberland School of Law]] is founded at [[Cumberland University]], in [[Lebanon, Tennessee]]. At the end of this year, only 15 law schools exist in the United States.\n* [[August 12]] &ndash; [[Mexican\u2013American War]]: U.S. troops of General [[Winfield Scott]] begin to advance along the [[aqueduct (water supply)|aqueduct]] around Lakes [[Lake Chalco|Chalco]] and [[Lake Xochimilco|Xochimilco]] in Mexico.\n* [[August 20]] &ndash; [[Mexican\u2013American War]] &ndash; [[Battle of Churubusco]]: U.S. troops defeat Mexican forces.\n* [[August]] &ndash; Yale Corporation establishes the first graduate school in the United States, as ''Department of Philosophy and the Arts'' (renamed ''Graduate School of Arts and Sciences'' in [[1892]]).\n* [[September 14]] &ndash; [[Mexican\u2013American War]]: U.S. general [[Winfield Scott]] [[Battle for Mexico City|enters Mexico City]], marking the end of organized Mexican resistance.\n* [[September 30]] &ndash; The [[Vegetarian Society]] is formed in the United Kingdom (it remains the oldest in the world).\n\n=== October&ndash;December ===\n* [[October]] &ndash; The last [[volcanic eruption]] of [[Mount Guntur]] in [[West Java]] occurs.\n* [[October 12]] &ndash; German inventors and industrialists [[Werner von Siemens]] and [[Johann Georg Halske]] found [[Siemens & Halske]] to develop the [[electrical telegraph]].\n* [[October 19]] &ndash; [[Charlotte Bront\u00eb]] publishes ''[[Jane Eyre]]'' under the pen name of Currer Bell in England.\n* [[October 31]] &ndash; [[Theta Delta Chi]] is founded as a social [[Fraternities and sororities|fraternity]] at [[Union College]], [[Schenectady, New York]].\n* [[November 3]]&ndash;[[November 29|29]] &ndash; [[Sonderbund War]]: In Switzerland, General [[Guillaume-Henri Dufour]]'s Federal Army defeats the ''Sonderbund'' (an alliance of seven [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] [[Cantons of Switzerland|cantons]]) in a civil war, with a total of only 86 deaths.\n* [[November 4]]&ndash;[[November 8|8]] &ndash; [[James Young Simpson]] discovers the [[anesthetic]] properties of [[chloroform]] and first uses it, successfully, on a patient, in an [[obstetric]] case in [[Edinburgh]].<ref>First communicated to the Medico-Chirurgical Society of Edinburgh, November 10, and published in a pamphlet, ''Notice of a New An\u00e6sthetic Agent'', in Edinburgh, November 12.</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Gordon|first=H. Laing|title=Sir James Young Simpson and Chloroform (1811\u20131870)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pYer05UwKBYC&ph=PA108|accessdate=2011-11-11|year=2002|publisher=Minerva Group, Inc|isbn=978-1-4102-0291-8}}</ref>\n* [[November 10]] &ndash; The first brew of [[Carlsberg Group|Carlsberg]] [[beer]] is finished in [[Copenhagen]].\n*  [[November 17]] &ndash; The Battle of Um Swayya Spring takes place near a spring in Qatar, after a Bahraini force under Shaikh Ali bin Khalifa Deputy Ruler of Bahrain defeats the Al Binali tribe. The chief of the Al Binali, Isa bin Tureef, is slain in battle with over 70 fatalities from his side. The battle secured the position of Shaikh Mohamed bin Khalifa\u2019s authority over the entire Qatar peninsula and is a setback for the rival branch Al Abdulla which relocated and separated earlier in the 1840s from Bahrain.\n* [[December 14]] &ndash; [[Emily Bront\u00eb]] and [[Anne Bront\u00eb]] publish ''[[Wuthering Heights]]'' and ''[[Agnes Grey]]'', respectively, in a 3-volume set under the pen names of Ellis Bell and Acton Bell in England.\n* [[December 21]] &ndash; [[Emir Abdelkader]] surrenders to the French in Algeria.\n\n=== Date unknown ===\n* The [[Great Famine (Ireland)|Great Famine]] continues in Ireland. \n* The [[North Carolina General Assembly]] incorporates the railroad town of [[Goldsboro, North Carolina|Goldsborough]], and the [[Wayne County, North Carolina|Wayne]] county seat is moved to the new town.\n* [[Radley College]], an [[English public school]], is founded near Oxford.\n* [[Welfare in Sweden]] takes its first step with the introduction of the ''[[1847 \u00e5rs fattigv\u00e5rdf\u00f6rordning]]''.\n\n== Births ==\n\n=== January ===\n* [[January 5]] &ndash; [[Oku Yasukata]], Japanese field marshal, leading figure in the early Imperial Japanese Army (d. [[1930]])\n* [[January 7]] &ndash; [[Caspar F. Goodrich]], American admiral (d. [[1925]])\n* [[January 24]] &ndash; [[Radomir Putnik]], Serbian field marshal (d. [[1917]])\n* [[January 27]] &ndash; [[Ella Maria Dietz Clymer]], American actress and author (d. [[1920]])\n* [[January 28]] &ndash; [[Dorus Rijkers]], Dutch naval hero (d. [[1928]])\n\n=== February ===\n* [[February 3]] &ndash; [[Warington Baden-Powell]], British admiralty lawyer (d. [[1921]])\n* [[February 5]] &ndash; [[Jo\u00e3o Maria Correia Ayres de Campos, 1st Count of Ameal]], Portuguese politician and antiquarian (d. [[1920]])\n* [[February 8]] &ndash; [[Hugh Price Hughes]], Methodist social reformer, first Superintendent of the [[West London Mission]] (d. [[1902]])\n* [[February 11]] &ndash; [[Thomas Alva Edison]], American inventor (d. [[1931]])\n* [[February 13]] &ndash; [[Sir Robert McAlpine, 1st Baronet|Sir Robert McAlpine]], Scottish builder (d. [[1930]])\n* [[February 15]] &ndash; [[Robert Fuchs]], Austrian composer (d. [[1927]])\n* [[February 16]] &ndash; [[Philipp Scharwenka]], Polish-German composer (d. [[1917]])\n* [[February 17]] &ndash; [[Otto Blehr]], Norwegian attorney, Liberal Party politician, 7th [[Prime Minister of Norway]] (d. [[1927]])\n\n=== March ===\n* [[March 1]] &ndash; [[Thomas Brock|Sir Thomas Brock]], English sculptor (d. [[1922]])\n* [[March 2]]\n** [[Isaac Barr]], Anglican clergyman, promoter of British colonial settlement schemes (d. [[1937]])\n** [[Cayetano Arellano]], first Chief Justice of the Supreme Court of the Philippines under the American Civil Government (d. [[1920]])\n* [[March 3]] &ndash; [[Alexander Graham Bell]], Scottish-born American inventor (d. [[1922]])\n* [[March 4]] &ndash; [[Carl Josef Bayer]], Austrian chemist (d. [[1904]])\n* [[March 14]] &ndash; [[Castro Alves]], Brazilian poet (d. [[1871]])\n* [[March 18]] &ndash; [[William O'Connell Bradley]], American politician from Kentucky (d. [[1914]])\n* [[March 23]] &ndash; [[Edmund Gurney]], British psychologist (d. [[1888]])\n* [[March 27]]\n** [[Otto Wallach]], German chemist, [[Nobel Prize]] laureate (d. [[1931]])\n** [[Garret Barry (piper)|Garret Barry]], Irish musician (d. [[1899]])\n\n=== April ===\n* [[April 2]] &ndash; [[Charles Frederic Moberly Bell]], British journalist, editor (d. [[1911]])\n* [[April 10]] &ndash; [[Joseph Pulitzer]], Hungarian-born journalist, newspaper publisher (d. [[1911]])\n* [[April 15]] &ndash; [[Yehudah Aryeh Leib Alter]], Polish Hasidic rabbi (d. [[1905]])\n* [[April 27]] &ndash; [[Emma Irene \u00c5str\u00f6m]], Finnish teacher, Finland's first female university graduate (d. [[1934]]\n\n=== May ===\n* [[May 7]] &ndash; [[Archibald Primrose, 5th Earl of Rosebery]], [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]] (d. [[1929]])\n* [[May 14]] &ndash; [[Frederick William Borden|Sir Frederick William Borden]], Canadian politician (d. [[1917]])\n\n=== June ===\n* [[June 8]]\n** [[Oleksander Barvinsky]], Ukrainian politician (d. [[1926]])\n** [[Ida Saxton McKinley]], [[First Lady of the United States]] (d. [[1907]])\n* [[June 10]] &ndash; [[Gina Krog]], Norwegian suffragist (d. [[1916]])\n* [[June 11]] &ndash; [[Millicent Fawcett|Dame Milicent Fawcett]], British suffragist (d. [[1929]])\n* [[June 16]] &ndash; [[Luella Dowd Smith]], American educator, author, and reformer (d. [[1941]])\n\n=== July ===\n[[File:President Hindenburg.jpg|thumb|right|110px|[[Paul von Hindenburg]]]]\n[[File:Bram Stoker 1906.jpg|thumb|right|110px|[[Bram Stoker]]]] \n* [[July 2]] &ndash; [[Marcel Alexandre Bertrand]], French geologist (d. [[1907]])\n* [[July 9]] &ndash; [[Wong Fei-hung]], Chinese healer, revolutionary (d. [[1925]])\n* [[July 19]] &ndash; [[Alexander Meyrick Broadley]], British historian (d. [[1916]])\n* [[July 20]]\n** [[Lord William Beresford]], Irish army officer, Victoria Cross recipient (d. [[1900]])\n** [[Max Liebermann]], German painter, printmaker (d. [[1935]])\n* [[July 25]] &ndash; [[Paul Langerhans]], German pathologist, biologist (d. [[1888]])\n\n=== August ===\n* [[August 3]] &ndash; [[John Hamilton-Gordon, 1st Marquess of Aberdeen and Temair]], Canadian politician, Governor General (d. [[1934]])\n* [[August 21]] &ndash; [[Hale Johnson]], [[American temperance movement]] leader (d. [[1902]])\n\n=== September ===\n* [[September 1]] &ndash; [[Archibald Kennedy, 3rd Marquess of Ailsa]] (d. [[1938]])\n* [[September 3]] &ndash; [[Charles Stillman Sperry]], American admiral (d. [[1911]])\n* [[September 5]]\n** [[Jesse James]], American outlaw (d. [[1882]])\n** [[Joseph Bucklin Bishop]], American journalist, publisher (d. [[1928]])\n* [[September 10]] &ndash; [[Franklin Bartlett]], American politician (d. [[1909]])\n* [[September 14]] &ndash; [[William Edward Ayrton]], English physicist, electrical engineer (d. [[1908]])\n* [[September 15]] &ndash; [[Tadeusz Browicz]], Polish pathologist (d. [[1928]])\n* [[September 16]] &ndash; [[Arthur Bromley]], British Royal Navy officer who became Admiral Superintendent of Malta Dockyard (d. [[1909]])\n* [[September 17]] &ndash; [[John I. Beggs]], American businessman (d. [[1925]])\n* [[September 22]] &ndash; [[Enrique Almaraz y Santos]], Spanish Catholic cardinal (d. [[1922]])\n* [[September 23]] &ndash; [[Anandamohan Bose]], Indian politician, academic and social reformer (d. [[1906]])\n* [[September 24]] &ndash; [[William Edward Briggs]], British politician (d. [[1903]])\n* [[September 25]] &ndash; [[Edward Austin (cricketer)]], English cricketer (d. [[1891]])\n* [[September 26]] &ndash; [[Wolf Wilhelm Friedrich von Baudissin]], German theologian (d. [[1926]])\n* [[September 30]]\n** [[Wilhelmina Drucker]], Dutch feminist (d. [[1925]])\n** [[Vilma Hugonnai]], Hungarian medical doctor (d. [[1922]])\n\n=== October ===\n[[File:Thomas F. Porter.png|thumb|110px|[[Thomas F. Porter]]]]\n* [[October 1]]\n** [[Sophia Amirajibi]], Georgian translator of poetry (d. [[1906]])\n** [[Annie Besant]], English women's rights activist, writer and orator (d. [[1933]])\n* [[October 2]] &ndash; [[Paul von Hindenburg]], German field marshal, [[President of Germany]] (d. [[1934]])\n* [[October 3]] &ndash; [[Lilian Whiting]], American journalist, editor, and author (d. [[1942]])\n* [[October 4]] &ndash; [[Louis Henri Boussenard]], French author of adventure novels (d. 